com.camerontec.catalys.util.data

Class AbstractTagValuesReadable

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.camerontec.catalys.util.data.AbstractTagValuesReadable
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    IBindable<ListIterator<ITagValue>>, ITagValueIterableFromTag<ListIterator<ITagValue>>, ITagValueIteratorBindable<ListIterator<ITagValue>>, ITagValuesReadable, Serializable, Cloneable, Iterable<ITagValue>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    AbstractTagValues

    public abstract class AbstractTagValuesReadable
extends Object
implements ITagValuesReadable
    This class provides a skeletal implementation of the ITagValuesReadable interface to minimize the effort required to implement this interface backed by a collection of ITagValue objects.

    To use this as a base for your own ITagValuesReadable implementation you need to provide implementations for the following methods:

    • clone() - the existing implementation which just calls Object.clone() is unlikely to be suitable.
    • ITagValuesReadable.getTagValue(int)
    • createIterator()
    • initIterator(java.util.ListIterator, int, ITagValue)
    • IBindable.isBindable(Object)

    Optionally, you may also want to override the following methods in order to provide a more efficient implementation than the default.

    • getTagValues()
    • hasField(int)
    See Also:
    Serialized Form

        public IValue getFieldValue(int tag)
        Default implementation is to call ITagValuesReadable.getTagValue(int) and return the IValue from the returned ITagValue.

        Retrieves the value of the first tag/value field with the given tag.

        Returns null or an IValue which is isUndefined, if no such field exists.

      • getTagValues

        public ITagValue[] getTagValues(int tag)
        Default implementation uses iterator() to iterate over all values, adding matches to a List, then the returned array is created from the List.

        This is not very efficient and you may want to override it with your own implementation.

        Note that in this implementation the returned array will not contain nulls or undefined tag values.

        Returns all ITagValues for a specific tag number in the form of an array.

      • getTagValues

        public ITagValue[] getTagValues()
        Default implementation uses iterator() to iterate over all values, adding each to a List, then the returned array is created from the List.

        This is not very efficient and you may want to override it with your own implementation.

        Note that in this default implementation the returned array will not contain nulls or undefined tag values.

        Returns all ITagValues in the form of an array.

        Because the returned array may be reused on subsequent calls to this method (depending on the implementation) you should not assume that the number of ITagValue's equals the length of the returned array. You should scan the array from the beginning until the end of the array is reached or a null value is encountered. Also note that depending on implementation the returned array can contain undefined tag values.

        Specified by:
        getTagValues in interface ITagValuesReadable
        Returns:
        Array of ITagValue's. Values are terminated by a null entry or the end of the array. Never returns null.
        See Also:
        IValue.isUndefined()

      • getTagValuesSortedByTagNumber

        public final ITagValue[] getTagValuesSortedByTagNumber()
        Default implementation calls getTagValues() and sorts the returned array in ascending tag order.

        Returns all ITagValues in the form of an array, sorted by the tag number of the ITagValue elements. Unlike ITagValuesReadable.getTagValues(), the array returned by this method will not contain undefined tag values and id not reusable, i.e. the number of ITagValue's will always equal the length of the returned array.

        Specified by:
        getTagValuesSortedByTagNumber in interface ITagValuesReadable
        Returns:
        Array of ITagValue's. Never returns null.

      • getValueAsDecimal

        public Decimal getValueAsDecimal(int tag)
                          throws ConversionException,
                                 MissingDataException
        Description copied from interface: ITagValuesReadable
        Returns the Decimal value of the first instance of a field with the given tag.

        Note that there is no explicit getValueAsDouble method. This method is used instead. Decimal values can be converted to double using the Decimal.doubleValue() method. Note also that you can perform arithmetic directly on Decimal objects using the methods Decimal.add(Decimal), Decimal.subtract(Decimal), Decimal.multiply(Decimal) and Decimal.divide(Decimal, int). So conversion to double (which is expensive and introduces precision issues) may not be necessary at all.

      • iterator

        public final ListIterator<ITagValue> iterator()
        Description copied from interface: ITagValueIterableFromTag
        Create an iterator over a collection of ITagValues.

        The following methods are not supported by the returned iterator:

        • java.util.ListIterator#remove()
        • java.util.ListIterator#add()
        • java.util.ListIterator#set()

        Calling any of them results in an UnsupportedOperationException.

        This method guarantees that a new iterator instance is returned with each call.

        The ITagValue objects returned are references to the underlying data, however, there are no guarantees regarding whether objects are created or not. Changing the values of these objects changes the underlying data. To avoid this behaviour you can use ITagValue.copyFrom(ITagValue) to copy the returned value before modifying it. If you intend on storing the returned ITagValue then copying it first is highly recommended.

        Specified by:
        iterator in interface ITagValueIterableFromTag<ListIterator<ITagValue>>
        Specified by:
        iterator in interface Iterable<ITagValue>
        Returns:
        Iterator over ITagValues. Guaranteed to be a new instance for each call.

      • iterator

        public final ListIterator<ITagValue> iterator(int tag)
        Description copied from interface: ITagValueIterableFromTag
        Create an iterator over a collection of ITagValues.

        This method has precisely the same semantics as ITagValueIterableFromTag.iterator(), except that iteration commences at the first instance of a ITagValue which contains the specified tag (if any).

        Specified by:
        iterator in interface ITagValueIterableFromTag<ListIterator<ITagValue>>
        Parameters:
        tag - The tag at which to start iteration. A tag ≤ 0 is considered out of range and implies the start of the collection. If multiple instances of this tag exist iteration commences at the first one.
        Returns:
        Iterator over ITagValues. Guaranteed to be a new iterator instance for each call.

      • bind

        public final ListIterator<ITagValue> bind(ListIterator<ITagValue> iterator,
                                          ITagValue buffer)
        Description copied from interface: ITagValueIteratorBindable
        Bind an iterator to a collection of ITagValues.

        This method binds the specified iterator to the collection of ITagValues and resets it to the start so that iteration is over the complete collection. If an attempt is made to pass an incompatible iterator type a ClassCastException is thrown. It is possible to check beforehand using the IBindable.isBindable(Object) method.

        The caller may specify the return value buffer. This is like to be very efficient and is guaranteed not to involve object creation. However, modifying the ITagValue entry during iteration has no effect.

        If no return value buffer is specified then modifying the ITagValue entry modifies the underlying data, however, there are no guarantees about object creation.

        Specified by:
        bind in interface ITagValueIteratorBindable<ListIterator<ITagValue>>
        Parameters:

      • bind

        public final ListIterator<ITagValue> bind(ListIterator<ITagValue> iterator,
                                          int tag,
                                          ITagValue buffer)
        Description copied from interface: ITagValueIteratorBindable
        Bind an iterator to a collection of ITagValues.

        This method has precisely the same semantics as ITagValueIteratorBindable.bind(Iterator, ITagValue), except that iteration commences at the first instance of a ITagValue which contains the specified tag (if any).

        Specified by:
        bind in interface ITagValueIteratorBindable<ListIterator<ITagValue>>
        Parameters:
        iterator - The iterator to bind to this collection. May be null, in which case a new iterator is created which is suitable for subsequent reuse.
        tag - The tag at which to start iteration. A tag ≤ 0 is considered out of range and implies the start of the collection. If multiple instances of this tag exist iteration commences at the first one.
        buffer - The buffer via which to return ITagValue entries. May be null in which cases the implementation chooses the most efficient return buffer. If supplied then modifying the returned ITagValue entries has no effect.
        Returns:
        Iterator over ITagValues using the supplied buffer to refer to each underlying element. The supplied iterator (provided it was not null) initialized to the start of the collection.

      • initIterator

        protected abstract ListIterator<ITagValue> initIterator(ListIterator<ITagValue> iterator,
                                                        int tag,
                                                        ITagValue buffer)
        Initialise the specified iterator for iteration from the specified tag using the specified return value buffer.
        Parameters:
        iterator - The iterator to initialize. May be null in which case a new iterator is created.
        tag - The tag from which to commence iteration. If this is ≤ 0 then iteration commences from the start of the collection.
        buffer - The return value buffer. May be null in which case the implementation determines the most efficient return value buffer.
        Returns:
        The initialized iterator.
        Throws:
        NoSuchElementException - If the specified tag is > 0 but does not exist in the collection.
        ClassCastException - If the specified iterator is of an incorrect type for the collection.
        See Also:
        createIterator()

      • isEqualTagValues

        public final boolean isEqualTagValues(ITagValuesReadable other,
                                      boolean strictOrder)
        Compares the specified ITagValuesReadable with this ITagValuesReadable for equality. Returns true if both objects contain the same ITagValue's. Additionally, if both objects are of the same type, the result of isEqualImplementation(ITagValuesReadable) is evaluated as well.
        Specified by:
        isEqualTagValues in interface ITagValuesReadable
        Parameters:
        other - ITagValuesReadable to be compared for equality with this ITagValuesReadable.
        strictOrder - if true the order of the tags is significant, otherwise this methods returns true even if the tag order is not the same, as long as both ITagValuesReadable contain the same ITagValues
        Returns:
        true If the specified ITagValuesReadable is not null and contains the same tags as this ITagValuesReadable.

      • isEqualImplementation

        protected boolean isEqualImplementation(ITagValuesReadable other)
        Always returns true here. Can be overwritten by subclasses to compare implementation specific details.

        This method is called by isEqualTagValues(ITagValuesReadable, boolean) if this.getClass().isAssignableFrom(other.getClass()).

        If you overwrite this method you probably should overwrite AbstractTagValues.copyImplementationDetailsFrom(ITagValues) as well.

        Parameters:
        other - ITagValuesReadable to be compared for equality with this ITagValuesReadable.
        Returns:
        If implementation details are equal
